    "John Trapp": "A wicked and adulterous generation] {See Trapp on \"Mt 12:39\"} The same wedge serves the same knot. They shall have no new answer from Christ, till they have made better use of the old. Let [v_Jer_15_19] them return to thee, not thou to them, #Jer 15:\n4. And when they looked ] Or, as some read it, when they looked up; for till now they may seem either to have gone plodding on with their eyes downward, or else to have looked on one another, as people use to do when they are conferring.\nVer.\n4. And when they looked] Or, as some read it, when they looked up; for till now they may seem either to have gone plodding on with their eyes downward, or else to have looked on one another, as people use to do when they are conferring.\nVer.",
    "R. Alan Culpepper": ", where the clause, \u201cfor it was very large\u201d (author\u2019s translation),\nshould naturally follow the women\u2019s question, \u201cWho will roll away the\nstone for us from the entrance to the tomb?\u201d in 16:3 rather than the\nreport that when they looked up they saw that the stone had been\nrolled back in 16:4a.15 The NRSV translation obscures the problem of\nthe misplaced \u201cfor\u201d clause by inserting it as an appositional clause in\n16:4a. Following this suggestion, the comment, \u201cfor it was not the\nseason for figs,\u201d in 11:13 should serve as an explanation for why Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\nwent to see if the tree had figs rather than as an explanation for why it\nhad nothing but leaves: \u201cThus, Mark\u2019s gar clause explains why Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\nhad doubts about whether he might find figs rather than why the tree\ndid not have figs.\u201d16 While this rearrangement relieves some of the\nincongruity of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 looking for figs when it was not the season for figs,\nit still does not lessen the difficulty of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 cursing the fig tree when it\ndid not bear figs out of season.\nAlternatively, Mark\u2019s comment can be seen as \u201ca signal that the story\nis to be read for its symbolic meaning.\u201d17 The word \u201cseason\u201d translates\nthe significant Greek term kairos that denotes not the chronological\n373\n[v_Mrk_11_1] [v_Mrk_11_2] [v_Mrk_11_3] [v_Mrk_11_4] [v_Mrk_11_5] [v_Mrk_11_6] [v_Mrk_11_7] [v_Mrk_11_8] [v_Mrk_11_9] [v_Mrk_11_10] [v_Mrk_11_11] [v_Mrk_11_12] [v_Mrk_11_13] [v_Mrk_11_14] [v_Mrk_11_15] [v_Mrk_11_16] [v_Mrk_11_17] [v_Mrk_11_18] [v_Mrk_11_19] [v_Mrk_11_20] [v_Mrk_11_21] [v_Mrk_11_22] [v_Mrk_11_23] [v_Mrk_11_24] [v_Mrk_11_25] [v_Mrk_11_26] [v_Mrk_11_27] [v_Mrk_11_28] [v_Mrk_11_29] [v_Mrk_11_30] [v_Mrk_11_31] [v_Mrk_11_32] [v_Mrk_11_33] Mark 11:1-33\npassing of time but a particularly significant period of time. Mark uses\nthe term in Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 thematic announcement of the coming of the\nkingdom in 1:",
