    "John Trapp": "And he left them, and departed] Because he saw his sweet words were even spilt upon them. Frustra lavantur Aethiopes et certatur cum hypocritis: none are more obstinate and obdurate.\nVer.\n19. He was received up, &amp;c. ] This St Luke more fully sets forth, #Lu 24:50,51 Ac 1:9 .\nVer.\n19. Ver.\n19. He was received up, &c.] This St Luke more fully sets [v_Luk_24_50] forth, #Lu 24:50,51 Ac 1:",
    "R. Alan Culpepper": "Neither is it likely that it is a reference to God\nin this instance.5 Vincent Taylor, therefore, proposed that \u201cthe lord\u201d is\nthe colt\u2019s owner. The response is directed not to the colt\u2019s owner but to\nbystanders, and the owner may have been with Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`.6 Nevertheless, it\nis hard to avoid the impression that Mark is playing on the overtones or\nelevated meaning of the term.\nWhen the disciples enter the village, they find the colt and are chal-\nlenged, just as Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` had said, and their response satisfies the bystanders.\nWhen the two disciples bring the colt to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, the others place their\ngarments upon it, for a saddle for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`. Others throw their garments\non the road before Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`. The two references to the garments here echo\nthe report that Bartimaeus cast his garment aside to make his way to\n[v_2Ki_9_13] Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (10:50). In 2 Kings 9:13, the people spread their garments on the\nsteps before Jehu and hail him, \u201cJehu is king!\u201d According to Plutarch,\nwhen Cato the Younger left his troops, the soldiers \u201cspread their gar-\nments at his feet and kissed his hand as he passed, an honour which the\nRomans at that time scarcely paid even to a very few of their generals\nand commanders-in-chief\u201d (Cato Minor 7).7\nOthers spread stibadas on the road before him. The translation of this\nterm is debated, with Craig Evans favoring \u201ctall grass\u201d8 and the Bauer-\nDanker lexicon rendering it \u201cleafy branches,\u201d while noting that the\nterm appears only here in the New Testament and does not occur in the\nSeptuagint or Philo.9 Perhaps because the word is unusual and impre-\n[v_Mat_21_8] cise, Matthew changes it to \u201cbranches from the trees\u201d (Matt 21:8) and\n[v_Jhn_12_13] John `[char_John_Ref]` to \u201cbranches of palm trees\u201d (John `[char_John_Ref]` 12:13). Carrying on the\nmetaphorical significance of \u201cthe way\u201d from earlier references (see\n10:52), the road into Jerusalem is still the way that will lead Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to the\ncross.\n370\n[v_Mrk_11_1] [v_Mrk_11_2] [v_Mrk_11_3] [v_Mrk_11_4] [v_Mrk_11_5] [v_Mrk_11_6] [v_Mrk_11_7] [v_Mrk_11_8] [v_Mrk_11_9] [v_Mrk_11_10] [v_Mrk_11_11] [v_Mrk_11_12] [v_Mrk_11_13] [v_Mrk_11_14] [v_Mrk_11_15] [v_Mrk_11_16] [v_Mrk_11_17] [v_Mrk_11_18] [v_Mrk_11_19] [v_Mrk_11_20] [v_Mrk_11_21] [v_Mrk_11_22] [v_Mrk_11_23] [v_Mrk_11_24] [v_Mrk_11_25] [v_Mrk_11_26] [v_Mrk_11_27] [v_Mrk_11_28] [v_Mrk_11_29] [v_Mrk_11_30] [v_Mrk_11_31] [v_Mrk_11_32] [v_Mrk_11_33] Mark 11:1-33\nLike other processions of pilgrims entering Jerusalem, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 followers\n[v_Psa_118_25] [v_Psa_118_26] sing and chant the words of one of the hallel psalms (Ps 118:25-26),\nperhaps antiphonally. Mark has carefully adapted the text of the psalm,\nhowever. Mark retains the Semitic \u201cHosanna\u201d rather than translating it\ninto Greek as the Septuagint does, rendering it \u201cSave us now\u201d (Ps\n117:25 LXX). Omitting the second half of"
